org.webchecker.watcher

Class ListenerGroup

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.webchecker.watcher.ListenerGroup

  • public class ListenerGroup
extends java.lang.Object
    Class represents a group of listeners. The rule of listeners grouping is that one group has only one source document to work on. This is the only thing connecting listeners in one group and each listener can (has to) have his own configuration.

    If listener wants to listen, he has to be in one or more groups. This group contains mechanism for auto listening and refreshing the source document and for explicit listening called by user.

    If you want to create a group, you have to specify a supplier able to supply fresh version of document. In this case, the supplier is represent by Supplier functional interface. Each listener contains the max age of document, that can be regarded as a fresh. If this parameter is not specify in constructor, the default value will be used.

    Version:
    1.0

      • newGroup

        public static ListenerGroup newGroup(@NotNull
                                     java.util.function.Supplier<org.jsoup.nodes.Document> document,
                                     long maxRefreshingDelay)
                              throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
        Returns a new group with given document supplier and max refreshing delay. Both arguments has to be valid. This means, that getDocument != null && maxRefreshingDelay &gt;= ListenerConfig.MIN_AUTO_CHECKING has to return true.
        Parameters:
        document - the document supplier for the new group
        maxRefreshingDelay - the max age of document, that can be int the new group regarded as a fresh
        Returns:
        new listener group with given parameters
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if given document is null or maximal refreshing delay is not valid
        See Also:
        ListenerGroup(java.util.function.Supplier, long), newGroup(java.util.function.Supplier), ListenerGroup

      • addListener

        public void addListener(Listener listener)
                 throws org.webchecker.watcher.ListenerGroup.AlreadyDestroyedException
        Configure the given listener and add it to the listeners list. If auto checking of the Listener is on, add it to worker's list to apply auto listening.
        Parameters:
        listener - a listener to be added; if it's null it won't be added to listeners list
        Throws:
        AlreadyDestroyedException - if Listener was already destroyed

      • addAllListeners

        public void addAllListeners(Listener... listeners)
                     throws org.webchecker.watcher.ListenerGroup.AlreadyDestroyedException
        Call the addListener(Listener) method for each listeners in given array.

        In fact, this do the same as: for(Listener l : listeners) { addListener(l); }

        Parameters:
        listeners - array of listeners to add by addListener(Listener) method
        Throws:
        AlreadyDestroyedException - if Listener was already destroyed
        org.webchecker.watcher.ListenerGroup.AlreadyDestroyedException

      • check

        public void check(java.util.function.Predicate<Listener> update)
           throws org.webchecker.watcher.ListenerGroup.AlreadyDestroyedException
        Apply listening to listeners, that return true for given predicate. If the last version of loaded document is not fresh enough, refresh it by refresh() method. A document is fresh enough when delay between his loading time and now is less than max refreshing delay.
        Parameters:
        update - this function has to determine, if we should apply listening to a listener
        Throws:
        AlreadyDestroyedException - if Listener was already destroyed
        org.webchecker.watcher.ListenerGroup.AlreadyDestroyedException

      • destroy

        public void destroy()
        Destroy this listener group. This mean that you will be not able to use this object. And if you try to, it will throw an AlreadyDestroyedException!

        This method should be called, when you know, that you will not use this group in the future.
